                <div class="jonra" data-uuid="a543427aec474cd0a4cde8b3ae88ffb1">
                    <h2 data-uuid="ef030d6f8ad54b0aa5385525bcb08d05">The Debate over Slavery</h2>
                    <p class="source" data-uuid="b499169edef1471db2d89d58c8e14dd5">Slavery was one of the most troubling issues at the Convention. The delegates debated whether slavery should be regulated or abolished, as well as how it should affect representation.</p>
                </div>
                <section class="compare-text" data-uuid="4e1fa70227bc40308979da520acc64dd">
                    <figure class="green-star intro-star" data-uuid="8228e7c880f1419b8f07c62ac281c2f2"></figure>
                    <article class="column-container intro-col" data-uuid="7cce3efd86474e15ab88a443d5432435">
                        <div data-uuid="6bec45b26be0410ba28d7c1607b83806">
                            <figure class="image-with-caption intro-pic" data-uuid="262042794b8b430cbebd75ba488774d4">
                                <img class="intro" alt="This is a portrait of Rufus King." src="../../img/prologue_lesson02/8_snlese454170_351p.png" data-uuid="63c0ab5201e7480b8d8efb09ac7ff98f" />
                            </figure>
                            <p class="caption" data-uuid="53e5d5ca6fe9487ebfd218adc15fcc73">Rufus King of Massachusetts was concerned about counting slaves to determine representation in Congress.</p>
                            <p class="red hang" data-uuid="8a2c4efbb722477aae798cbc3011a66b">”[I] had hoped that . . . at least a time would have been limited for the importation of slaves. [I] never could agree to let them be imported without limitation and then be represented in the National Legislature.”</p>
                            <p class="source" data-uuid="4a6a01aee92c4ed2b656cba0b2c6721d">—Rufus King</p>
                            <p class="source small" data-uuid="2cfe1ddc6bea4ac593bab7ae344e7fca">quoted in <i>The Records of the Federal Convention of 1787, </i>edited by Max Farrand</p>
                        </div>
                        <div data-uuid="952fa0b574b640e3bfdea93eb92deb58">
                            <aside class="col-2-begin-container" data-uuid="3d2292673f1242dcbeb5506ed0901af3">
                                <figure class="image-with-caption intro-pic" data-uuid="94b6badcb53b47479fac6a9de7646500">
                                    <img class="intro" alt="This is a portrait of John Rutledge." src="../../img/module_6_lesson01/ms_snlese454149_236p.png" data-uuid="2f2f42a0e23b42f29de56ea580a901ac" />
                                </figure>
                                <p class="caption" data-uuid="8fca23cdb30e4615889dab98ad7fd59d">John Rutledge of South Carolina strongly defended the practice of slavery.</p>
                            </aside>
                            <p class="blue-2 hang" data-uuid="ac29d9e9ea4d4d568385000b93de1f91">“If the Convention thinks that North Carolina, South Carolina, and Georgia will ever agree to the plan [to prohibit the slave trade] unless their right to import slaves be untouched, the expectation is <b><a href="[remark:a556a4bb572c41c9b5e0199cdbd3edd0]"> vain</a></b>.”</p>
                            <p class="source" data-uuid="b75dd90c2cf7458cbeee172e1b9b2a9c">—John Rutledge</p>
                            <p class="source small" data-uuid="7aeddb4aa076458fb03f65ab1f40dcc7">quoted in <i>The Atlantic Monthly, </i>February 1891, by Frank Gaylord Cook</p>
                        </div>
                    </article>
